Class AbstractBatchAndIncrementalLearner<DataType,ResultType>

  • java.lang.Object
    • gov.sandia.cognition.util.AbstractCloneableSerializable
      • gov.sandia.cognition.learning.algorithm.AbstractBatchAndIncrementalLearner<DataType,ResultType>
  • Type Parameters:
    DataType - Type of the input data. Typically an iterable or a collection.
    ResultType - Result type from both the online- and batch-learning interfaces.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    BatchAndIncrementalLearner<DataType,ResultType>, BatchLearner<java.util.Collection<? extends DataType>,ResultType>, IncrementalLearner<DataType,ResultType>, CloneableSerializable, java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    AbstractConjugatePriorBayesianEstimator, AbstractIncrementalEstimator, AbstractKalmanFilter, AbstractParticleFilter, AbstractSupervisedBatchAndIncrementalLearner, DefaultDataDistribution.Estimator, DefaultDataDistribution.WeightedEstimator, OnlineMultiPerceptron, ScalarDataDistribution.Estimator, SimpleStatisticalSpellingCorrector.Learner, VectorNaiveBayesCategorizer.OnlineLearner

    public abstract class AbstractBatchAndIncrementalLearner<DataType,ResultType>
extends AbstractCloneableSerializable
implements BatchAndIncrementalLearner<DataType,ResultType>
    An abstract class that has both batch learning ability as well as online learning ability by taking a Collection of input data. For the batch learning case, we iterate over the Collection of input data and pass this through the online learning function to arrive at the batch result.
    Since:
    3.0
    Author:
    Kevin R. Dixon, Justin Basilico

      • clone

        public AbstractBatchAndIncrementalLearner<DataType,ResultType> clone()
        Description copied from class: AbstractCloneableSerializable
        This makes public the clone method on the Object class and removes the exception that it throws. Its default behavior is to automatically create a clone of the exact type of object that the clone is called on and to copy all primitives but to keep all references, which means it is a shallow copy. Extensions of this class may want to override this method (but call super.clone() to implement a "smart copy". That is, to target the most common use case for creating a copy of the object. Because of the default behavior being a shallow copy, extending classes only need to handle fields that need to have a deeper copy (or those that need to be reset). Some of the methods in ObjectUtil may be helpful in implementing a custom clone method. Note: The contract of this method is that you must use super.clone() as the basis for your implementation.
